{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 14:52:46.036103", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report — multi‑tier Clos (EBGP) lab\nContents: executive summary, observed symptoms, evidence collected, localization, root‑cause analysis, impact and additional observations.\n\n1) Executive summary\n- Overall control-plane (BGP) appears healthy: all expected prefixes (10.0.x.0/24 and 10.1.x.0/24) are present in BGP on super‑spine, spines and leaves and next‑hop selection looks consistent across routers.\n- Data-plane user symptom: host pc_0_0 is intermittently/unreachably failing to ping remote host subnets while other hosts (e.g., pc_0_1 and many others) can reach those subnets normally.\n- Root anomaly localized to leaf_router_0_0: that router’s kernel RIB contains an unexpected \"unreachable (blackhole)\" entry for 10.0.0.0/24 which correlates with pc_0_0 reachability failures.\n\n2) Observed symptoms\n- From the reachability sweep:\n  - pc_0_0 -> remote hosts (e.g., 10.1.0.2 and 10.1.2.2): status reported \"unknown\" (no successful ping).\n  - Other hosts (pc_0_1, pc_0_2, pc_0_3, pc_1_x) show successful pings (0% loss, reasonable RTTs).\n- Control-plane: all routers show the full set of prefixes in their BGP tables; super‑spine, spines and leaves are advertising/receiving those subnets.\n\n3) Key evidence (excerpts)\n- Reachability summary (selected):\n  - pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2) -> 10.1.0.2 : status \"unknown\"\n  - pc_0_1 (10.0.1.2) -> 10.1.0.2 : ok (0% loss; rtt ~2 ms)\n- leaf_router_0_0 ip route (relevant lines):\n  - K * 10.0.0.0/24 [0/0] unreachable (blackhole), 00:00:36\n  - C>* 10.0.0.0/24 is directly connected, eth4, 00:01:02\n  - Connected 172.16.0.32/31, 172.16.0.40/31, 172.16.0.48/31, 172.16.0.56/31 present\n- leaf_router_0_0 BGP table:\n  - *> 10.0.0.0/24 0.0.0.0 (origin i) — i.e., prefix locally originated/advertised via BGP\n  - Other 10.1.x/24 prefixes shown with expected next‑hops\n\n4) Localization — faulty device(s)\n- Primary device: leaf_router_0_0\n  - Evidence: kernel RIB entry \"unreachable (blackhole)\" for the 10.0.0.0/24 network on leaf_router_0_0 coexisting with a connected route; the host attached to that subnet (pc_0_0) shows failed/unknown reachability while other hosts function normally.\n- No evidence of global BGP session loss: BGP tables on spines and super‑spine show all prefixes (so prefix propagation is intact). Spines/super‑spine do not show abnormalities.\n\n5) Root‑cause analysis (most likely)\n- The immediate root cause of pc_0_0’s lack of connectivity is the kernel blackhole route for 10.0.0.0/24 on leaf_router_0_0. When a prefix is installed in the kernel as \"unreachable (blackhole)\" packets destined to that prefix will be dropped locally, producing the observed data‑plane failure for the directly connected host.\n- How this arose (plausible causes, based on evidence):\n  - A RIB synchronization issue between FRR and the kernel RIB (FRR or an external process recently installed a blackhole route), or\n  - A stale/manual kernel route entry (an administrator or an automated process created an unreachable route), or\n  - A transient routing event where FRR attempted to remove/reinstall the connected prefix and a blackhole route remained installed.\n- Important nuance: BGP still sees and advertises the 10.0.0.0/24 network (FRR shows it as locally originated). That indicates the control-plane advertisement is present even while the kernel has an inconsistent local route state — i.e., the problem is at RIB/FIB/kernel route level on leaf_router_0_0, not at BGP adjacency or prefix advertisement to neighbors.\n\n6) Impact\n- Host impact: pc_0_0 cannot reliably reach other subnets (evidence: ping failures). Other hosts (including pc_0_1) are not affected.\n- Network-wide routing: BGP propagation remains intact; remote routers have routes to 10.0.0.0/24. However, traffic destined to the local host may be blackholed at leaf_router_0_0 if that kernel unreachable route is installed in FIB/forwarding plane.\n- Potential for asymmetric behavior: since remote routers have routes to 10.0.0.0/24, return traffic may reach leaf_router_0_0, but if the leaf’s kernel drops packets for the prefix (blackhole), packets will be dropped locally — causing full connectivity loss for the attached host.\n\n7) Additional observations and notes\n- Time markers in the leaf_router_0_0 route output: blackhole entry shows age 00:00:36 while the connected route shows 00:01:02. Both entries existing simultaneously is abnormal — typically the connected route should be the FIB entry for the directly attached prefix. The coexistence suggests a race or duplicate RIB sources.\n- Interface naming/numbering: the route output lists the connected prefix on eth4 whereas the topology lists leaf_router_0_0:eth2 connecting to pc_0_0. This discrepancy could be benign (different naming convention in the device config) but is worth noting in case the interface referenced by the router does not match the intended physical link.\n- No other routers show kernel blackholes for the /24 prefixes — the anomaly is localized to leaf_router_0_0.\n\n8) Recommended next investigation steps (for context only, not remediation)\n- Verify kernel route origin on leaf_router_0_0 (show kernel route details, check FRR RIB-to-kernel sync logs) and check the interface state of the connected interface for 10.0.0.0/24.\n- Check FRR logs on leaf_router_0_0 for recent route install/withdraw events that would explain a blackhole entry.\n(You asked to not provide mitigations; these items are suggested investigative steps only.)\n\nClosing summary\n- Control-plane (BGP) healthy and consistent across devices.\n- Data-plane problem for pc_0_0 is caused by a kernel \"unreachable (blackhole)\" route for 10.0.0.0/24 on leaf_router_0_0. This is the primary anomaly and explains the observed host reachability failures.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_to